r lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/><a:t>14 phalanges</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr marL="171450" indent="-171450"><a:buFont typeface="Arial"/><a:buChar char="•"/></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/><a:t>The carpal bones are arranged in two rows.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr marL="171450" indent="-171450"><a:buFont typeface="Arial"/><a:buChar char="•"/></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/><a:t>The proximal row includes the scaphoid, lunate, triquetrum, and pisiform.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr marL="171450" indent="-171450"><a:buFont typeface="Arial"/><a:buChar char="•"/></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/><a:t>The distal row includes the trapezium, trapezoid, capitate, and hamate.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr marL="171450" indent="-171450"><a:buFont typeface="Arial"/><a:buChar char="•"/></a:pPr><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/><a:t>The scaphoid, lunate, and triquetrum bones articulate with the radius and articular disc of the radio-ulnar joint.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr marL="171450" indent="-171450"><a:buFont typeface="Arial"/><a:buChar char="•"/></a:pPr><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="700" dirty="0"/><a:t>* A mnemonic for remembering the carpal bones is “Scary Lunatics Try Poisons That They Can’t Handle.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" sz="700" dirty="0"/></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" sz="700" dirty="0"/><a:t>The first letter of each word is the first letter of each of the bones from lateral to medial, proximal row first.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/></a:p><a:p><a:pPr marL="171450" indent="-171450"><a:buFont typeface="Arial"/><a:buChar char="•"/></a:pPr><a:endParaRPr lang="en-US" sz="800" dirty="0"/></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:cxnSp><p:nvCxnSpPr><p:cNvPr id="65" name="Straight Connector 64"/><p:cNvCxnSpPr/><p:nvPr/></p:nvCxnSpPr><p:spPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="8686800" y="3276600"/><a:ext cx